Dear Friends ! 
As we complete Sarga 182, I feel Mahārṣi Vasiṣṭha has quietly taken us on a remarkable pilgrimage.
We began beneath a Kadamba tree.
We watched sincere seekers undertake tapas.
We witnessed boons, human longing, love, separation, and the compassion of the Divine Mother.
We questioned the possibility of many worlds.
And then, without fanfare, Vasiṣṭha turned the entire story inside out.
The chapter is not really about eight brothers.
It is not about seven continents.
It is not even about extraordinary austerities.
It is about our own mind, our deepest aspiration, and finally the Pure Consciousness in which all aspirations, worlds, and stories arise.
This is what makes the Yoga Vāsiṣṭha unique among the great scriptures.
It does not stop at inspiring us.
It does not stop at teaching morality.
It does not even stop at devotion.
It gently removes every support until only the Self remains—silent, complete, ever-free, and self-luminous.
To me, the hidden jewel of Sarga 182 is this:
Every journey in the world eventually reaches its destination.
The journey to the Self ends with the discovery that we never truly left It.
